text.Taxonomy and naming:
Boronia scabra was first formally described in 1839 by John Lindley and the description was published in A Sketch of the Vegetation of the Swan River Colony. The specific epithet (scabra) is a Latin word meaning "rough", "scurfy" or "scabby".In 1998, Paul Wilson described three subspecies that are accepted by the Australian Plant Census:

Boronia scabra subsp. attenuata Paul G.Wilson has flowers that sometimes have five sepals and petals;
Boronia scabra subsp. condensata Paul G.Wilson has rough stamen filaments;
Boronia scabra Lindl. scabra has smooth stamen filaments.
